The handheld device, a relic scavenged from the ruins of the old data hub, crackled to life in Klaus’s grip. It wasn’t the usual automated weather report or the sterile, scheduled check-in from the greenhouse’s central AI. This was… noise. Static, yes, but underneath it, something else. A voice? Impossible. They were the only ones left who used this frequency, this ancient communication band thought long dead. He held it to his ear, fingers tightening around the worn casing.

The voice on the other end was faint, distorted by time and the vast, desolate silence that lay between them. It was young, laced with confusion. It spoke of things that felt like ghosts – traffic, busy streets, the mundane sounds of a world that had ceased to exist a century ago. Klaus leaned against the wall of the dome’s observation deck, looking out at the bruised, grey sky and the skeletal remains of skyscrapers swallowed by the mutated flora. The contrast was jarring.

He responded cautiously at first, his professional training kicking in. He identified himself, stated his location – Dome 7, Sector Gamma, former North America – and the current date and time – December 31st, 23:55, 2125. The silence on the other end stretched, heavy and disbelieving.

